diff --git a/docs/RISK_EXTERNAL_INTEGRATION_1_IMPORT_TIME_REDIS_INIT.md b/docs/RISK_EXTERNAL_INTEGRATION_1_IMPORT_TIME_REDIS_INIT.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..8c4f984
--- /dev/null
+++ b/docs/RISK_EXTERNAL_INTEGRATION_1_IMPORT_TIME_REDIS_INIT.md
@@ -0,0 +1,55 @@
+# Risk: External Integration Import-Time Redis Initialization
+
+## Status
+Open. Operational resilience risk.
+
+## Severity
+P1 operational resilience
+
+## Current behavior
+`backend/app/services/external_integration_service.py` creates Redis connection at module import time:
+
+- `REDIS_CONN = Redis.from_url(settings.REDIS_QUEUE_URL)`
+
+This connection object is later used by:
+
+- `ExternalIntegrationService.enqueue_appointment()`
+
+## Why this is a risk
+The module has an import-time side effect.
+
+If Redis queue configuration becomes invalid, missing, malformed, or unexpectedly incompatible,
+the module may fail too early during import or service startup, before the system reaches its
+intended fail-safe enqueue behavior.
+
+This weakens startup resilience and makes failure handling less explicit.
+
+## Why this is not currently a launch blocker
+Current enqueue logic is fail-safe for callers:
+
+- enqueue errors are caught
+- caller does not crash
+- function returns `False`
+
+So the direct runtime integration path is already partially hardened.
+
+## Architectural conclusion
+Current implementation is acceptable for launch baseline, but not ideal.
+
+Redis queue connection initialization should be converted to lazy initialization,
+so queue connection is created only at the moment of actual enqueue usage.
+
+## Recommended future change
+Replace import-time global initialization with one of:
+
+- local `Redis.from_url(...)` inside `enqueue_appointment()`
+- dedicated lazy getter for queue connection
+- shared queue factory with explicit error handling and logging
+
+## Trigger for redesign
+Prioritize redesign when any of the following happens:
+
+- startup/import instability appears in production
+- Redis configuration becomes environment-dependent across deployments
+- queue/integration layer is expanded
+- stricter service readiness guarantees are required
diff --git a/docs/RISK_SCHEDULING_1_SINGLE_RESOURCE_PER_SHOP.md b/docs/RISK_SCHEDULING_1_SINGLE_RESOURCE_PER_SHOP.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..8c902fc
--- /dev/null
+++ b/docs/RISK_SCHEDULING_1_SINGLE_RESOURCE_PER_SHOP.md
@@ -0,0 +1,77 @@
+# Risk: Single Resource Scheduling Per Shop
+
+## Status
+Open. Accepted launch limitation.
+
+## Severity
+P1 domain limitation
+
+## Current behavior
+Appointments are protected from overlap by the database constraint:
+
+`appointments_no_overlap_per_shop`
+
+The constraint is defined on:
+
+- `shop_id`
+- `tstzrange(start_time, end_time, '[)')`
+
+Active statuses included:
+
+- `NEW`
+- `CONFIRMED`
+- `IN_PROGRESS`
+
+## Confirmed schema reality
+The `appointments` table currently has no dedicated planning resource field such as:
+
+- `resource_id`
+- `bay_id`
+- `operator_id`
+- `capacity`
+- `slot_capacity`
+
+Therefore the current effective scheduling model is:
+
+**one schedulable resource per shop**
+
+## Why current behavior is valid
+For the current launch baseline, this behavior is internally consistent:
+one appointment occupying a time slot blocks the whole shop.
+
+This prevents double booking under the existing STO launch model.
+
+## Why this becomes a future risk
+This model will produce false conflicts if the product evolves to support:
+
+- multiple service bays
+- multiple operators working in parallel
+- parallel capacity within one shop
+- resource-specific calendars
+- partial slot allocation
+
+## Architectural conclusion
+Current constraint is accepted as a **launch-safe baseline**.
+
+It must be redesigned when resource-based scheduling is introduced.
+
+## Recommended future migration target
+Replace overlap protection from:
+
+- `shop_id + time range`
+
+to one of:
+
+- `resource_id + time range`
+- `shop_id + bay_id + time range`
+- `shop_id + operator_id + time range`
+
+depending on the final scheduling domain model.
+
+## Trigger for redesign
+Redesign becomes mandatory immediately when any of the following appears in scope:
+
+- service bay scheduling
+- operator scheduling
+- parallel bookings in one shop
+- capacity-based slot allocation
--
